TY  - JOUR
T1  - A sensitivity analysis of the effective protection estimate
AU  - Yeats, Alexander J.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 3
IS  - 4
SP  - 367
EP  - 376
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(76)90030-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387876900304
AB  - While numerous empirical studies have evaluated the effective protection afforded by tariffs of developed nations, recent investigations have applied the concept to LDCs. However, a point that has been overlooked is that production costs and value added in many developing countries lack the stability these elements assume in industrial nations. Since production information constitutes a key input, any given (point) estimate of the ERP may be misleading unless some indication as to its variability is also shown. Using production data from three developing countries (Sri Lanka, Iran and Pakistan) this study empirically tests the sensitivity of the effective protection estimate to short-term changes in value added. The results indicate that this coefficient is sufficiently volatile to render point estimates of the effective rate inaccurate as measures of both the level and distribution of industry protection.
